Invoking: `validate` with `{'patch': '--- a/Modules/_cursesmodule.c\n+++ b/Modules/_cursesmodule.c\n@@ -3368,9 +3368,15 @@\n     if (curses_initscr_called) {\n-        wrefresh(stdscr);\n-        return (PyObject *)PyCursesWindow_New(stdscr, NULL);\n+        if (stdscr == NULL) {\n+            _cursesmodule_state *state = get_cursesmodule_state(module);\n+            PyErr_SetString(state->error, catchall_NULL);\n+            return NULL;\n+        }\n+        wrefresh(stdscr);\n+        return (PyObject *)PyCursesWindow_New(stdscr, NULL);\n     }\n'}`
responded: The bug is in this code:

```c
if (curses_initscr_called) {
    wrefresh(stdscr);
    return (PyObject *)PyCursesWindow_New(stdscr, NULL);
}
```

If `curses_initscr_called` is true, but for some reason `stdscr` is still NULL (for example, a previous call to `initscr` failed or the terminal resources were released), this would lead to a NULL pointer dereference.

The correct patch is to check that `stdscr` is non-NULL before calling `wrefresh(stdscr)` and constructing the new window object.

Here is the patch:

```diff
--- a/Modules/_cursesmodule.c
+++ b/Modules/_cursesmodule.c
@@ -3368,9 +3368,15 @@
     if (curses_initscr_called) {
-        wrefresh(stdscr);
-        return (PyObject *)PyCursesWindow_New(stdscr, NULL);
+        if (stdscr == NULL) {
+            _cursesmodule_state *state = get_cursesmodule_state(module);
+            PyErr_SetString(state->error, catchall_NULL);
+            return NULL;
+        }
+        wrefresh(stdscr);
+        return (PyObject *)PyCursesWindow_New(stdscr, NULL);
     }
```

