The root cause of the null dereference is in this block, from the ASan report and code review:
```c
if (curses_initscr_called) {
    wrefresh(stdscr);
    return (PyObject *)PyCursesWindow_New(stdscr, NULL);
}
```
If `curses_initscr_called` is set, the function uses `stdscr` directly **without checking if it is NULL** (which can happen if previous initialization failed, or under some edge cases). Both `wrefresh(stdscr)` and `PyCursesWindow_New(stdscr, NULL)` will crash if `stdscr == NULL`.

**Patch objective:**
Add a NULL check for `stdscr` in the `if (curses_initscr_called)` block to ensure we don’t dereference it.

Here is the patch:
```diff
--- a/Modules/_cursesmodule.c
+++ b/Modules/_cursesmodule.c
@@ -3368,10 +3368,18 @@
     if (curses_initscr_called) {
-        wrefresh(stdscr);
-        return (PyObject *)PyCursesWindow_New(stdscr, NULL);
+        if (stdscr == NULL) {
+            _cursesmodule_state *state = get_cursesmodule_state(module);
+            PyErr_SetString(state->error, catchall_NULL);
+            return NULL;
+        }
+        wrefresh(stdscr);
+        return (PyObject *)PyCursesWindow_New(stdscr, NULL);
     }

     win = initscr();

     if (win == NULL) {
         _cursesmodule_state *state = get_cursesmodule_state(module);
         PyErr_SetString(state->error, catchall_NULL);
         return NULL;
     }
```

